\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 I don't know the address but I - he}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955158\charrsid13784614  was come from Ca}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 rnarvon. My mother come from Jersey. And they - how my mother come to be born in Jersey, her father was one of the guards over Nap}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955158\charrsid13784614 o}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
leon. When Napoleon died the Regiment got dispersed and he settled in Jersey. Well my mother was one of the children well when she left - and she left Jersey in the time near enough when the - Lilley Langtrey, the 
Jersey Lilly my mother called her - they were quite proud of it not as it made any difference to her and - she was - come to London, straight from Jersey to London, met my father, I don't know how they met but they met and they got married - my mother and
 
father lived after they got married down a court the side of Greenwich church, the houses are still there. Greenwich church, by Greenwich church. There's a courtway down the side of the church and the houses are still there where they lived when they got 
m
arried. After that they come over to South East of London, Elephant, Blackfriars, Waterloo and all round here, and that's all they seemed to - got no further, only them districts, that's why they were known as the two biggest drunkards in Waterloo and Bla
ckfriars.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your mother work before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
My mother work? Well - no, I don't, but I know where she worked when she was married, when I was a - a child. She worked in Covent Garden, shelling peas, peeling potatoes for the Savoy Hotel 
in Cherry Brothers in Covent Garden. There by the National Sporting - where there used to be the National Sporting Club.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 She used to prepare the vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 That}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955158\charrsid13784614 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 s right, yes. About a dozen women and when they pick their money up about eighteen
 pence, something like that, they used to go down Wellington Street, about a - what would be - you know, some went straight home, but the others went into that pub next to the Lyceum, Theater on the corner of the Strand and Wellington Street and got drunk
 on what they earned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your mother work regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did she do any other sort of part time work or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Only cleaning and that. Charring and that, cleaning. Used to go doorstep cleaning down Kennington Park
 Road you know, 'cos they were all actors down there well you know, Charlie Chaplin's mother and father were down there. In fact she worked for - Charlie Chaplin's father and mother down in Kennington Park Road - only cleaning doorsteps you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you know your father's occupational history, was he always a coal heaver?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - his father was a well-to-do man. He was a - used to buy up land for the timber what was on 'em and he used to get men as what they called pit sawyers, see, they didn't ha
ve machinery in them days. One man was down the hole and another above and - and my father worked for him some time but he finished up in Mays Hill Greenwich as an undertaker, and my father took me and my sister Emma over to there one night, you know, ear
l
y in the afternoon and of course my father and my grandfather got on the booze and - we couldn't get back so they put me in one coffin and my sister in another one and they both slept on - one slept on the floor and the other one slept on the bed, a small
 \{ILLEGIBLE\} bed. I can remember that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Your grandfather was on his own by then was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes. 'Course he left 'em four hundred pounds each to four brothers. But I don't know my father's brothers. But - he left -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 It was quite a lot of money then wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you know what other sort of work your father did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. Well he didn't always do the coal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955158\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 work. Timber. Yes, timber porter off the - unload b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955158\charrsid13784614 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
rdes and ships, timer porter. Cement - offloading -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Mainly the heavy stevedore work was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, it was. Very heavy work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 He did this sort of work all his life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 All his life, yes. A very strong man. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Who looked after you children when your mother was at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 They used to let us have the run of the streets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So you didn't have a babysitter or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, no. I - 'course my mother and father used to get - you know - for drunke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14955158\charrsid13784614 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 ness they used to go and do a - like seven days or fourteen days and me or wh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955158\charrsid13784614 o}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
ever was at home at the time used to go round to a sister or a brother who was old enough to take us in 'til they came out. And then they got another room and then they took us back. Not for long. They soon got drink and got inside. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You being the youngest had married sisters to go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you stay with anyone of your married sisters in particular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, sister Jenny. She - her husband was a - a son of the richest man ever known in the Borough. South east 1. N
ear London Bridge or the Borough Market. He left 250,000 and the son - the - one of the sons, still trying to find out where he lived but he'll never find it. And he had this - he had - four sons. One had one eye. Used to look after Barrons, Horse's Head,
 
in the Borough Market. The other brother, my sister Ginny's husband, he used to go round with a pony and cart with four or five - lengths of lino, but it - not congoleum like this it was proper lino, 'cos his father had factories in Ireland, lino factorie
s, and Belgium and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember your father being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh yes, yes. And when they used to go to the casual ward for relief he use to stop in the casual ward for about a week chopping up wood so that he'd be earning us children and his wife, who was my mother, relief. Yes, that was the system in those days.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Which house do you remember as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Vernon Street. London Road. S.E.1.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You were there for quite a time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, I can remember - my mother and father were there some time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Could you tell me how many rooms there were in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Two. Oh, in the whole house? There was two - four - four - four rooms in that house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your family have all these rooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Two rooms. Two rooms upstairs. One
 room downstairs as you go in the door, one room is on the left, two brothers had that, comedians on the stage, contortionists and all that. On the other side, on the right hand side was an old man, a navy. And my mother looked after him because - he got 
a pick axe in the middle of his leg and it ulcerated, my mother looked after him there. We lived in that house to my knowledge - twelve month. Well just near enough twelve months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters live with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Only me, my father and my mother, and a sister used to come round now and again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So you were at home on your own by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Your other brothers and sisters were away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your mother ever pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 This old man that your mother looked after, did he pay her at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh well not - you know - a wage, he used to give her a couple of shillings and all that but - she was good hearted, she used to spend that couple of shi
llings on bandage and lint. Yes. So you couldn't call it a wage. But she was good hearted, I don't mind saying that. Although she was very vicious. Very vicious. I was in hospital about eighteen months with the leg and my mother never missed a visiting da
y
 which was only - I think it was a Thursday afternoon and a Sunday afternoon - for eighteen months my mother never missed a visit and my father never come up and see me once. And yet my father never laid a hand on us children. And my mother in her drink s
he was very vicious. Think nothing of getting hold you and throwing you on the floor, jumping on you, scratching all down the face. In her drink mind you. But when she was sobered up she couldn't do enough for you. Funny.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How old were you when you were living at this house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 I should think eight years old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Was the washing done at home or was it sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh it used to be done at home in a bath on two chairs in front of the window. And the - of course they were coal fires and a pot of wa
ter on the hob that side, pot of water on the hob this side, and it was all done in a bath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were your clothes new or second hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Clothes? Always second hand. Of the barrows down the market place. Penny left and happenny right we used to call th
em. Oh you could buy boots in them days I can remember when they were in the money you could buy a brand spanking new pair of boots for half a crown, hobnail. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you used to buy second hand shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Always. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your mother or father ever make or mend the family clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh - repairs, you know, sewing them up and all that. But - in regard to bedclothes, sheeting, my mother never bought sheets out of a drapers shop. She used to buy scenery out the Victoria - Vic - the Victoria 
- Vic we called it, you know the opera house in Waterloo Road, used to buy the old scenery - fetch it home, put it in a bath in the yard and let it soak for about a week. And when that was - done two or three times we had - had a bed sheet - you could nev
er tear 'em. My mother never used to buy new sheets because the old man, he used to - you know - in his drink he used to flop on the bed in his coal clothes and everything see. So what was the good of sheets? So that's what she used to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your father help in the house at all, would he do any washing up or cooking or anything?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What him? No. He was the guvnor and he never - I don't know - he had - no -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 He wouldn't do anything at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 He was very cruel to her. He used to hit her like
 he'd hit a man. Yes. Although my mother's a big strong woman. He'd hit her like he'd hit a man. He was a strong man and all. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Would he do anything like bringing up the coal for the fires or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Nothing at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, not him - he was never in. The only time he was in he'd come - come home and get sober, then go out again and get drunk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So you didn't see much of him in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did he ever bath the children or tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. No. Nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you have any regular tasks to carry out in the home to help your mother or father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 I used to go for all the errands and that but - 'course there was none of the others there when I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you have to do anything else in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Go and get the coals and - sometimes if I took a fit in me head I used to sweep up and all that. But my mother would never let me - try and scrub the floor. 'Cos we never had no lino, it was all bare floors in there. We used to ma
ke a workshop - we had one room, that was the only time we had two rooms as I say in Vernon Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You usually had one room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Always one room. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You'd have to cook and everything in the one room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Everything on the one fireplac
e. 'Cos we never had a - very rare we had a gas stove 'cos - it - gas was very cheap then, five hours a penny, put a penny in the slot it lasted five hours. But it was very rare we had a gas stove. Always had a coal fire.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were you expected to be in bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. I went out at - twelve o'clock, one o'clock in the morning, playing with the other boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Bedtime wasn't considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, no, no. That's the reason they put me away to charity schools, not in a - a truant 
school, see they found a - a - she kept a small chandlers shop you know sold ha'porth of milk and ha'porth of tea and sugar and all that. When she retired she had a bit of money, she thought she'd do some good to it so she had me put to charity schools an
d paid for me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Was this one of the like corner shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Yes. You know, used to sell a farthing worths of milk, a ha'porth of tea and a ha'porth of sugar and bread was a only three ha'pence a loaf then, with overweight as big as the loaf. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - I - I can only remember once when my father come home for him to do anything good because I was so cold that I laid on the bed with the cold and whether it was the cramp or not I don't know, I can
't remember what it was - he came in, he see me laying on the bed with me - one leg, 'cos I couldn't bed this leg - this leg up like that, I couldn't do it with this leg. What's the matter Tommy? I said, oh I've got a pain in my stomach. So he says, well 
t
ake your clothes off. Oh no, don't take it off. I can remember the words. Oh no, don't take the clothes off he said. Look, he said, have you had any tea? I said, yes, I've been down the Gospel Lighthouse with all the other boys and girls. I said, we had -
 bread and jam down there. 'Cos we used to go to all the mission halls, one nearly every night, bread and fish night, bread and jam night, that's how we used to live most of us in the South East of London, Bermondsey and Southwark.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You didn't eat at home much then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Where did the family - what did your mother and father do for meals, where did your family have their meals then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well Sundays - always had a regular meal on a Sunday, and - it was always the - 'course how - why 
we had it on a Sunday - Saturday we - I was the only one and - the brother, the youngest brother of the two - Samuel - Sam - Jerry they used to call him - we used to all have a - a place to go to buy food. I used to go Jermyn Street for twopennorth of gib
l
ets. We lived in Waterloo - Waterloo or Blackfriars or - as I say we were never in one place long - I - my regular jobs was Jermyn Street, two pennorth of giblets, you know, that was the insides of chickens, the liver and all that. Another one had to go o
v
er the Strand, stale bread. Yes. That's how we used to - to - another one used to have to go to - Harts Corner, it's there, still there now. Two pennorth of block ornaments we used - they used to - they knew. What do you want? Two pennorth of block orname
n
ts. Right-o. Oh about five or six pounds of good meat. 'Course they didn't have no fridges in them days. So it was better meat then than what you get today. What you get today is twelve months old they reckon. But - having no fridges it was either sell it
 or give it away or throw it away you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So you used to do a lot of shopping on Saturday nights?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes, shops is open up 'til ten - ten o'clock at night. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of meals would you have on Sunday, what would you have for Sunday breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - if it was - if we got a - a large - you know, bit of a joint we used to have a - a roast, done in front of the fire on what they called a Dutch oven. Pot on one side, pot on this and Dutch oven in the front. And - 'course it was c
oal - it was good coal although it was only about a shilling or one and two or one and four a hundredweight then, but it was good coal, English coal. But - the last coal they got here, cheap coal, was Belgian coal, no good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Could you tell me when breakfast was eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - the old man used to go out at four or half past, but he didn't have a breakfast. He didn't have one, he used to have it in a coffee shop, he didn't have a breakfast. He had - go down the brewery, Lion Brewery where he's - get 
a lot of job and other breweries and they used to have it down there. My mother used to get up about five and she used to go down to Covent Garden, start shelling peas, peeling potatoes, I can remember nearly every morning I used to go over the coffee sho
p, cup of tea and a slice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You used to have to get yourself up for school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your mother bake her own bread or make jam or anything like this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 She didn't do any cooking or preserving at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, No. 
She was a good cook but she didn't make her own bread, bread was so cheap you know, I mean it's cheaper to make - to buy it than make it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How about wines or medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well we only had one medicine. Had it up on the shelf up the top and we had t
o have that every weekend and there's about - very likely three or four of us - and after taking this medicine we was all dashing down the stairs for the lavatory 'cos the - she used to have a sheet up on the line separate one room, make two of it, we - u
s children slept one side and father and mother the other side. And with that medicine - when we knew it was coming we used to get out but she used to stop us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What was it, was it liquorice powder or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, it was - household mixture they called it, but we didn't call it household mixture. You can guess what we called it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What room did you bath in then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 All in the one room. In the ordinary bath you know. You know, the old tin bath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How often was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 About 
- oh - my mother was - strict on us having a bath once a week. Oh yes. Yes. She used to bath one, dry us, put our clothes on, go on, hoppit. Then one of the sisters used to have her bath. Bath her, clothe her again, go on, hoppit, go - go down the court, 
play down the court.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 When did you have clean clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - mother was all right for clothes, she used to do her regular washing once a week. Oh yes. Sometimes she used to go to the public baths - very rare - always done it at home in a bath on 
two chairs, same bath we bathed in she used to - wash the clothes in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your mother or father grow any of their own vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did they buy any tinned or dried vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Any what? Tinned? Oh yes. All tinned milk nearly in those days. Goat Brand. Three pence \endash  five pence ha'penny a tin.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember any other tinned stuff you used to have in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, there wasn't a lot of tinned stuff about in those days. Never get tinned peas or tinned potatoes and tinned this and tinned that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 It was just milk you used to use?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Mostly - yes. 'Course you used to go and get a farthings worth of milk you know in those days. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did they keep any livestock for the family, any hens or rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
No. I did - keep some mice once, I made a cage and - I had no glass so I took a picture down, took the glass out of the picture for the front of the mouse cage. My mother come home and she sat down and she - about half an hour she was looking at t
his picture. Where'd that bloody glass worn out that picture? Of course, she see the cage. Wallop, I get the wallop. She didn't hit us hard you know, with the flat of her hand. But always had a cane up on the line, ha'penny cane. Every oil shop had a bund
l
e of canes you know - cane and - 'course what we used to do we used to break the cane up or chuck it out. Where's the cane? Here y'are, go down the oil shop and get a ha'penny cane. Never without a cane. Oh yes, common - common. And they didn't call - my 
f
ather didn't call candles candles. They used to call 'em composites. He'd say, go down the oil-shop, get four composites. I'd go down the oil shop, I'd say, four composites? The man in the shop used to say, composites? What are they? I said, you know, wha
t
 you light for a light. So he went over. He said, do you mean these? I said, yes. He said, they're not composites. I said, my father told me to come and get 'em. Where's your father come from? I said, Wales. He said, they're candles, not composites, he sa
id, I've never heard of it before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 It's a Welsh expression?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, I suppose it was, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How many times a week did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - very rare at home. We mostly had our dinners in school, 'cos you know the old milk churns, well they
 used to be delivered at all the school-board for London, then that - the - after it was the L.C.C. but they were big milk churns delivered at the school full of soup, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 This would be pretty good soup would it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh it was good soup. And if - 
when we wasn't at school - 'cos I was a rare one for hoping the wag, was what I used to do to get away from school I used to get a button, you know, well any - mostly a button with a deep - bone button and I used to press it in me throat just before I wen
t
 into class see, and I used to go up to the headmistress and say - mother said could you tell me what this was? Oh - ringworms, oh. I was away from school three or four months at a time. Yes. Over Covent Garden with a sack, a sack full of broken up wood, 
y
ou know, flower boxes, back over Waterloo Bridge, down Fennison Street where Waterloo station is now, knock at a door, firewood ma'am? How much? Tuppence the bagful. No, give you a penny or threeha'pence. No. All right. Shoot it down the - you know - the 
a
rea and back - over the Garden, four or five times and - earn about eight pence or something like - used to go over Berts, Farringdon Street, next to Hents Corner, a packet of envelopes and paper, in a pub - 'cos you was allowed in - we used to play on th
e sawdust in pubs then - envelopes and paper, penny a packet. I'd sell a packet - that was a - I'd earned four pence out of that. Back again for another \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 that's how we used to get hold of money. No, we never used to get anything out of home our parents, not pocket money any way. They never had enough for their beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You didn't used to get pocket money off your parents then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh now and again you know, a ha'penny or a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Not regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, not regular - when they thought they would, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Still if you could earn eight pence or ten pence in a day like that you weren't too bad off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh I've earnt as much as - three bob. Yes. And once I earnt a pound in a day, Guy Fawkes. Yes. When we went over the Embankment and - me 
and two other boys - and we had the Guy and they were chucking taters at us and all that at that Guy, you know, these - hansom cab drivers. You know, hansom cabs. Only two wheels. I don't know if you remember horse - no - hansom cab. The four wheelers the
y
 called the growlers. Yes. Well - when we reckoned up we had - somewhere about eleven o'clock in the morning, finished up about nine o'clock at night, when we counted up a pound. And - me and one boy, half each. The other boy never got nothing. See? So it
 
come to a fight. He fought me first and - then he fought the other fellow. He still got nothing. He - we was in the corner shop stuffing ourself and he was sitting on the other seat with nothing. Oh that was when we wearned a pound that day on the Guy Faw
kes time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What did you used to do with the money you earned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 I - banker.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Gamble - card games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes, back horses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 While you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, go down to Copeys in East Lane, Wilbur, three pence each way. We lived 
down East Lane, Hard Street they called it. Oh it was a terrible street. My mother and father had - oh we had - I forgot that one, there was two rooms there we had and - we moved in there and on the same night, was in bed about one o'clock in the morning,
 
bang bang bang bang bang bang. My old man got up, he said, what the f'ing hell's going on here? They'd only been - that's the first day used been in that home. There's a turning out of East Lane, Walworth - he get up, what the hell's the - what the f'ing 
h
ell's the matter here? The costermongers only fetching their ponies through the passage, we didn't know they had a stable out in the yard. Yes. The horse doing all down the passage. Oh what a life. But - it's true though, I'm not making it up. If I could 
f
ind some of the old 'uns you know like myself, they'd sell you the same thing. And yet we was happy. That's funny. Never wanted a meal, because we knew all the shops where we could go and get a soup ticket. Oh we had a dozen shops. And we used to go to a 
m
ission hall nearly every night. Bread and jam night, bread and fish night, all like that. And we used to go away once - once a year or twice a year for a fortnights holiday, Princes Christians Home, Windsor. Two of them turn outs a year we used to get. Ye
s
. Oh we - used to try and teach us - Shaftesbury Hall, we used to go to them a lot. Now I think they got broke up or something 'cos - they gathered so much money on charity - what they got stopped for they only used to share out two shillings and eighteen
 shillings theirself. They got stopped at it. That was Ahafetsbury Hall people. But they weren't the only people mind you. All these here big people you know - looking after the poor, they were looking after theirself. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh no, share and share alike. Oh yes, yes. Oh no, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Would your father need extra?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well he was very rare at home. He always had his meals out or in the pub. His breakfast was
 three ha'porth of bread and cheese and a pint of ale. That was his breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 He rarely ate at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, very rare he was at home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were you allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Talk? Oh yes. But - we were never allowed to put our arms on the table, like that. Get them arms off. Wallop. You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to have a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh whatever she got we had to have. Yes. We couldn't pick and choose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What was your parents attitude if you left some of the food uneaten, would they make you eat it or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh no, they didn't force us, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask someone to pass it to you or did you just help yourself?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, helped ourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 If there was any, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Any time we wanted to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you say grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. No, not - neither of them were religious. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Could you bring books or toys to the table during mealtimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. To put a knife in our mouth - you got a 
hiding for that. Yes. Oh she had - taught us good manners as far as she cold go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How was the meal served?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh - very haphazard like you know. Pot of 'tatoes - the potatoes come out and smacked on your plate - meat - I always used to say, I don't want that fat, I don't like fat. You've got to eat some fat.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So she'd bring the pots just off the fire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 To the plates on the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well newspaper on the table, pot used to come off the hob onto the - onto the paper, dished out 
like that see. Frying pan was used for meat, fish and anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What order were you served in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - the biggest ones you know used to get theirs first, then - what do you want - how much to you want? See. And we, the littlest ones, we were served last.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Was she an affectionate sort of person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, oh yes, she had her feelings. Give her her due there. As I say, in her drink, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 If you had any worries could you share them with your mother or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - as I say, she was good hearted in that way - she thought - as I - eighteen months she never missed a visit at hospital see, so you - guess that she was a good hearted woman to us children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How about your father, was he an easy man to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, oh yes, he was all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Could you share your worries with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh he wouldn't listen to 'em, he was a - he a big gambler. Very big gambler he was. He named me after a race hors
e. Yes. My name is Thomas Jones, I mean - he told me after when I, you know, bit grown up, he said, do you know what, he said, I think it was 1896, he said, I backed a horse called Tommy Tittlemouse. He says, a couple of days after, 'cos you know it was b
ig money they won, about - three or four pound, see that was big money then, I named you after that racehorse, Tommy Tittlemouse, so your name - that's how your name become Thomas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 He was quite affectionate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes, yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well they didn't seem to care much, they used to let us have the run of the streets then, that's trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, they didn't trouble about that. He was always fighting one another, us brothers we were always fighting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did they say you should hit back if another child hurt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes, not half. I'd come up crying because I'd got a wallop off anothe
r kid, my mother - what's up? So and so's hit me in the eye. Well go down and if you don't hit him in the eye I'm going to give you the other eye. And she'd make me go down and fight the boy or the girl, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well I don't know what their hopes were because I don't think they troubled. They didn't trouble. Yes. Things as they come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Didn't take no notice 'cos they was the biggest swearers agoing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So they didn't bother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Was this fairly general do you think in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 If you did something your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - you got a slapping see. But - as I - in - in their drink you got a hiding what they called a hiding. But when sh
e was sober we got a slapping. Two different moods you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did she use the cane very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Not half. But she knew where to hit us properly. Never in the head or shoulders. Always on the backside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your father ever punish you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 I can never remember my father hitting me or any of my brothers or sisters. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Not even when he'd had a drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 But you say he would hit your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh not half. I've seen 'em stand up - I can remember several times -
 stand in the middle of the room - he get hold of her, punch her, she'd punch into him back and they'd finish up on the floor, both of them, punching at one another. Yes. Oh they were very crude that - that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember any particular occasions when you were punished, anything that stands out in your mind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - as I said, we used to all get together, play up at - in the court or the street or the road where we lived and we'd be playing up there twelve o'clock, half past twelve, one o'cl
ock in the morning, see. And - I can remember occasion when we had all stopped out, slept in some bu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7358159\charrsid13784614 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
ldings underneath, some in the lavatory, some under the sink, Westminster Bridge Road, opposite Oakley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7358159\charrsid13784614 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
s where they made the glass paper, and - we got - hi
ding for that, she was going to put us away and all that but she didn't. And that was - I remember then when the smallpox was about, there was twenty - twenty-two people who lived in that house - there was eight - eight, nine - ten people died in that hou
se and the rest of us who was alive stood up in a corner and had this - thing squirted all over us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 I was about eight then. Yes. Oh that was - you know we had the 'flu at the first war? Well that was like the smallpox was t
hen. Everybody was walking about with a red band round their - say you'd got inoculated all that. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember how you felt about being punished when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, I didn't used to sulk - used to scream and shout and holler at b
eing - you know - for - sounded like we was being murdered but anyhow - after she'd give us a good hiding we used to get out and go down and - what's the matter Tom? Oh the old woman a in't half hit me. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Soon forgotten was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Woul
d you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, they were about the same. Yes, about the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. Used to take no notice of birthdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You didn't get a card or anything at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember anything you did with your mother or father together on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - we used to go in the pub with 'e
m, us children. See, 'cos you were - children were allowed in the pubs then and we used to play down in - on the floor in the sawdust and men who used to spit down there. And - all the women used to sit on the seat pealing the 'tatoes and - and shelling t
heir peas and - of course they was mopping it up all the time and us kids used to be playing in the sawdust, spit and all that, but - after a while - I think it was about 19 - about 1904 they stopped it. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So Christmas would be spent in the pub would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - I don't suppose we was ever at home at Christmas time, we all went to a Christmas party at some mission. See? That was the usual thing for all the poor kids then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of things would happen at this mission, what do you remember of Christmas at these missions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - what we used to - well take any one, they were nearly all the same. And we used to sing a few hymns and they used to have a magic lantern service, Twinkle, twinkle little star or something - then they'd s
how as a few pictures of different lands you know and - after that they used to say - well - we'll come and have the - cocoa and buns or biscuits, whatever it was, and that was the meal there. When we was at Shaftesbury Hall - in Trinity Street, Borough, 
w
e used to get a proper Christmas dinner there you see. We used to have turkey and - yes, 'cos turkeys, you could buy turkeys five shillings each then. When they used to buy it wholesale it used to be about half a crown. So they could feed a lot on one tur
key.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did they organize games or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well we used to go to - fretwork.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 At Christmas particularly I mean, did these missions give you a toy at Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes, yes, off a tree. Yes, off a tree. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you have any musical instruments in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh no. Not pianos - 'course the pianos was - it wasn't a home really without a piano, but we never had a piano. A mouth organ or a Jews Harp, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you ever make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Mouth organ, yes. One of my - one of my two brothers used to play the mouth organ, we used to all sit on the floor and join in all the songs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You say women used to peel their potatoes in the pub and this sort of thing, was this a regular thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Yes. Common - it was common. 'Course I'm only talking about the Borough, Bermondsey, Southwark, so I don't know whether it - well some parts of London were a bit you know sedate we know but - Bermondsey - yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your parents ever play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were there any books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Or magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Comics. Plenty of comics, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How about newspapers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh always a sporting paper. The Echo or The Star.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember your mother or father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Reading to us? No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 They'd never read out loud to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
No. No. 'Course if they wanted to sit round the fire and have a jaw or a chat they'd say, come on, go on, down the court or down the street, get with the boy
s and girls see. And we - seemed to be in their way somehow if they wanted a chat. If they didn't want to sit round the fire they was round the pub and that's it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So if your mother and father were having an evening indoors you'd be out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 That's r
ight. 'Course when they were out - we generally fetch one or two - boys and girls up and play ludo or something like that or snakes and ladders, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So that gave you the run of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes, oh we was boss then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember a funeral in the family before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Funeral? Well - I can remember - the only funeral I can remember - well it wasn't a funeral, it was a wake. It was my sister Ginny's - grandfather - like father. He was - a rank Irish name of Roache. He was a 
- I told you he was a pioneer of lino. And rank Catholic. They - what I can remember it was a court in the Borough opposite Rolands where they - Rolands paregoric tablets, I don't know if you ever - no you wouldn't, you wouldn't be old enough. It was a na
r
row court - only - well they couldn't get a table down. Used to take it right the way round the back way to get into this 'ere place, but the court itself was only about wide enough to get a chair down, see. Two people couldn't pass one at a time. That wa
s - facing - the debtors prison in the Borough. It's still there the debtors prison.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How old were you when you went to this funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well that - well it wasn't a funeral, it was a wake. I can remember it - just before I went in hospital with this
 leg. Only about five minutes walk away was the hospital in Southwark Bridge Road, facing the fire station. The hospital's still there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How old were you when you went into hospital there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Four and a half, five.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So you'd be very young indeed when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Yes. But I can remember that wake. Us kids was playing on the floor. Big room it was. And - the coffin was - standing up and leaning back, and us kids was playing on the floor and - my mother and father - the old - one or two o
f the oldest, you know, the oldest ones and neighbours, they were all drinking. And we was playing on the floor and I can remember looking over to the man, old Roache, and - he was laid in the coffin, and I happened to look and somebody threw a fag end in
 
the coffin. So I got up and I said go my mother, mother, mother. What? Properly drunk like. That man in the coffin is alight, look. What? She looked over and she shouted, old Roache is alight, he's alight, he's alight. They all got their cans of beer and 
jugs of beer and slung it all in the coffin to put the - I can remember that distinctly. Yes. Oh he was a funny man, old Roache.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember whether they were dressed in mourning clothes or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Everybody had mourning suits and the women
 had mourning dresses - made to measure. 'Cos they had special shops where they used to do nothing else but mourning clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Your mother and father had them made too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 It would be quite an expen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7358159\charrsid13784614 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 e for them wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
No. They were cheap. Yes. 'Cos I mean to say, you could buy a suit for about ten bob. A man could buy a good suit for eighteen shillings. And when I used to go to an outing or anything my - my turn out was a ha'penny paper collar. All us kids, ha'penny 
paper collars. 'Cos when we got home they were torn up, we lit the fire with them then. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were you ever taken out visiting neighbours or friends or relations at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes, we used to go to other neighbours places and play in their place on the floor with their children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you ever go visiting with your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No - I can't remember going to - going to anywhere special.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You say you have one memory of seeing your grandfather with your father and sleeping in the coffin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
That's the only remembrance I had of my grandfather, when he took me and my sister over to Maize Hill and they both got drunk. And it was so late all the buses had - 'course they were horse buses then and - couldn't get home and I was put i
n one coffin, she was put in the other. The only time I can remember my grandfather.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were you ever taken out shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh used to go out shopping with me mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 When you wanted clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - the shops was open up - it was common f
or them to be open at ten o'clock at night see. And I used to go with my mother, here you are, take this bag, put the 'tatoes in, peas was sold in pods then, but they didn't used to weigh 'em, they used to measure the peas then. Be sold by the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7358159\charrsid13784614 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 ottle and t
hat was the biggest cheating way a going, 'cos my brother, the one who used to be the costermonger, he used to say to me - he had a stall down the Cut, near the Victoria - Vic - look after the barrow, anybody come up - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7358159\charrsid13784614 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 ottle of peas. I'd say - put 'em in and push 'em down. And my brother come along, what the bleeding hell you doing, he said, co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7358159\charrsid13784614 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
 blimey, I'm losing money. He said, when you measure 'em out, he said, get 'em like that and go like that, don't press 'em. Used to get about half a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7358159\charrsid13784614 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 ottle for a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7358159\charrsid13784614 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 ottle that way see. 'Course it was stopped over that thing you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Is that why they started selling them by weight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes, over that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well now and again used to go out you know. Always in a pub. Yes. Yes. Always in a pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember any other outings with your parents, and Bank Holidays or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - yes. I can remember going to Mitcham on the horse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7358159\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 trams, me my mother and my father on the old horse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7358159\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 tram and - one
 part of the journey we all had to get out the tram and walk, because it was such a steep hill, see. And when we got to Miccham it was a warm watercress ground there and my father used to say now, look, if ever you got a black eye, all you've got to do is
 get one or two of those things put it on your eye, he said, that'll take all the black blood out. I forget what they call them now, they're like slugs. Used to swim amongst the watercress.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you ever go away for a holiday, a weeks holiday or anything like this in the summer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Could you tell me about these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - I went three times to Princes Christian Home, Windsor from a mission a hall called the Gospel Lighthouse, that was in Red Cross Street, Borough. We used to go - ma
ny - lots of days outings by brakes you know, these four horse brakes that they had. Only a little way out. Mitcham, places like that. Not long distance, 'cause horses ain't like cars and charabancs today. Yes.
