- some - in the castle itself, there was only one article there, a big peacock, all diamonds. But we wasn't allowed to go in, but me, I - I dashed in and starts - come on, come on, you know, the - guide who was taking us round, 'course we've had privilege
 that nobody else had you see. Yes. And - another place we used to go was - Southernside of the gasworks. The house is still there but not as a con}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid421377\charrsid13784614 v}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 al-scent home now, or holiday home. And what - last time I remember going there, the matron says to me, look 
Tommy Jones, she said, I'm going to give you sixpence if you take the boy in a wheelchair, she said, and give him a good wheel round. Of course, sixpence is a lot of money for us kids then. So I said, oh yes matron. She said - whatever you do, she said, d
o
n't take him near the water. Well at right at the side of the pier belongs to the gasworks there, there's a big opyn gate - what - I said to the other boys, come on, lets put him down on the sand and we can go up and spend our tanner. So he says, yes. So 
w
e pushed him down a bit too far, well when we come back about two hours after the water's right up to his knees. 'Course we got a ticking off for that. 'Course I daresay you remember the gasworks there. They'd got a bit of a pier going out in the water yo
u
 see. Well one side was the wall - no, it wasn't a wall, it was more of a - onto a - off the pavement onto the sand. But the other side was a bit of a brick wall and a - a big opening. Pushed him - why we pushed him through that sand but we did to spend t
hat tanner.
