ver Waterloo Bridge, sell it down Tennision Street, where the Waterloo station is now. Tuppence or three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid421377\charrsid13784614  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
pence. Back over again, get another sack of wood. That's where we used to get our pocket money from.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You'd be earning money on a Saturday would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh yes. Yes. Yes. 'Cos - what we used to do - I don't know if I told you to stop away from school for three months I used to press a button - I told you that. And - yes, and - we used to go over Convent Garden, 'course Convent Garden used to close
 about two o'clock. Well we used to get what we could out the firewood, go back over Blackfriars Bridge, in Berts, next to Harts corner, get a dozen envelopes and paper and round the pubs and all that lark, matches and all that sort - just to get money. Y
e
s. 'Course they had no control - my father and mother never had no control over me, 'cause I was the only one left, all the others left home before they were twelve year old, somebody took 'em in. You know. I had a well-to-do sister, she was a - a nurse i
n Romford hospital, but my mother's sister adopted here and - yes. And - her husband was a big sea captain, of course he had plenty of money. He could afford to have her sent to college. But all the others we were - oh - do what we liked.
