ous trouble but somehow or other I escaped it. She put her hand up and said - 'course - mind you it's not a word that should be used but - it's used today more than what it is - was then. She said I called her a c. See? She put her hand up, see, so she sa
i
d, yes, what's the matter? Tommy Jones called me a c. But she didn't say c, she said he called her a nasty name? What name did he call you? She said, well it begins with c. So - the teacher said, well come out here. Goes up to the desk. Write down what he
 
called you. Of course she wrote the full word down. So after little bit - come out here Tommy Hones. Can you read that? I said, yes. Oh, I said, that's terrible in't it? Ooh ah. You know, I used me wits. So she said, did you use that word. I said, no, I d
i
dn't. Did you call her that? I said, oh yes, I called her something 'cos she was - she was kept on pulling me back and pushing me over I said. What did you call her? I said, I called her a big cat. So she didn't know whether to believe the girl or believe
 me. So anyhow I got the benefit of the doubt. Mrs Hare, I remember her name now. She was a good old girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What happened if you did something the teachers disapproved of, how would they punish you at that school?
