\insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 tism.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 I think I was about - thirteen - near enough. That's when I got the job as a van boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Would you have stayed any longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 But you did go to another school afterwards didn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. Not when I left the Old Kent Road school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What was this apprentice place you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
When I - about thirteen when I left school. I didn't go back no more. I got a job as a van boy. Right. Well when he found out that I wasn't fourteen -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 This was the chap who employed you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Yes. Only a - you know one van man, he had a horse and van and a traction engine from London to Cobham. And - he used to - come home, he used to work Billingsgate, Borough Market and all that, load, he'd come back to the yard and w
e used to have to shift all the lot onto the traction engine. Then he used to say, come on, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 j}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
ump up and we used to have to go to Cobham, that's about eight o'clock at night. Time we got to Cobham it's about one or two o'clock in the morning, un-load and co
me back again. Go out and have some breakfast, if there was any, and - start work again. Oh yes, he had no - there weren't no one very soft there I'll tell you. No. And - after I got the sack I remember I was laying in bed one morning about half past nine
, this 'ere ward - more like a - you know - constable in plain clothes, he walked in, he didn't - knock, you know, knock or anything. I was in bed and so he come over to the bed, 'cos we only had the one room in St Margaret}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 s Court - come on, what are you d
oing in bed this time, come on, he said, I've come up to take you over Spring Gardens. I said, what for? I said, I'm not going to no school. He said, this is no school, he said. So he says, come on. And I was in pain with this leg at the time. Anyhow I ho
b
bled over Blackfriars - onto the embankment, right the way down to the embankment, the other end was - you know, Spring Gardens was - it always was facing - County Hall now, see, they shifted from Spring Gardens when they started - when they built the - w
h
en I got over there I had to go in front of - of a great big table, they was all round it, and one says, to me, oh good morning, Tommy. Well, we're going to ask you whether you'd like to go in for a trade. So I said, yes. What would you like to be? I said
, a boot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 maker. I remember - distinctly remember - a boot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
maker. So they all, yap, yap yap, yap all around the table - I see. All right. All right. You know, they give me a book to read, a paragraph or a simple sum. I done it. All right, right. Well - we'll see what we can do for you to be a boot}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
maker. I said, thank you. And this 'ere fellow, big ex-copper he was, come on, come on. So one spoke to him about don't be too rough with him, see. Oh he was a brutal fellow. So after that he was all right. Well, we
 walked - round - down the Embankment again see, over Blackfriars Bridge, when we got over there he said - any breakfast? I said, you know I ain't. So he says, well come on. He took me in this 'ere coffee shop, oh rough old coffee shop because it was all 
f
ull of cockroaches all in the window. So he took me in so he said, what do you want? So says, oh I don't care. So he says, you going to have some eggs and bacon? Quite nice to what he was. So I suppose they'd ticked him off see. So he says - all right, I 
s
aid, I'll have; two eggs - two eggs and a rasher. I can remember the two eggs and a rasher. Of course you know the lot only come to sixpence. Cup of coffee, 'cos it was tea, coffee and cocoa then, they had three urns, tea, coffee and cocoa. Well I - I pre
f
erred coffee at the time. When he paid, I don't know what it come to exactly but anyhow you could get the lot for sixpence at the time. He went out, left me. Well about three weeks after we got a letter from Chailey to say I'd been accepted. This lady had
 sponsored me and paid for me. The L.C.C. didn't. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 It was a private sponsor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Yes. It was a - elderly kept a - a grocer - a little grocery shop like. When she retired being old I suppose she thought she'd do some good with the money she'd earned. Well she sponsored me, I think it was sixty pound a year she paid at Chailey for me.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you ever meet this lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Never. I've never seen her. The only - the last time I see her she took me up to Camberwell - big park at Camberwell Green and 
she said, all right you have a run round. She sat down on a seat and I run round or hobbled round somehow. And she said, oh, she said, you're quite strong on that leg. I said, yes, that's all right. Well - when we came home she spoke to my mother. That wa
s the last I see of that woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You only saw her the once?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 That's all, once only, that's when she took me to Green Park - Camberwell Park.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How long were you at this training place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Chailey - Newark and Chailey - 1904 or '05, I was there three years. And then - we were taught to be - see, I asked to be a boot}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 maker, but when I got there the - they trained us to be cabinet makers, not boot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 makers. Well - I was too rough for the cabinet makers so they made a carpenter of me. After three ye
ars they sent six of us to Brighton in a mineral water factory, name of R. Fry's, mineral water people. Not. R. Frys the chocolate people. Mineral water people, Middle Street, Brighton. I was there about - two and a half - two and a half - two - to two an
d
 a half years and then - I let myself go and come back to London. Then I got on the best way I could. And yet I still went in the - in the building trade. Oh yes. I finished up at the Mount Pleasant Post Office as a carpenter there. Working for the Minist
ry of Works, not the Post Office itself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You worked as a carpenter in the building trade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Yes. And I used to climb ladders, a kit of tools on me back and - I got about - of course a lot of them dubious about taking me on but - yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Could you tell me about this training school, how you lived and this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Newark and Chailey. Yes. Well I - I don't want to sort the papers out but I've got some of the papers here now. I am the oldest one there. Can't find any of the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did they teach you anything else except cabinet making?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
No, only cabinet making. We had our own bench, we had our own bench, we had our own machinery there - had all our own timber yard there. It was run by Lady Kimmins and her friend - Miss Rennie -
 Miss Kimmins - Mrs Kimmins, her husband was Doctor Kimmins of the L.C.C. in - you know, the big place there now. Not Spring Gardens, opposite - the big building. County Hall. Yee -. Doctor Kimmins.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you actually make things for sale there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Y
es. Yes. We made - well they started off on simple things such as toys you see, and they worked us up to a - a gatelegged table and all that sort of thing. All what we used to make was all sent away to be sold and they used to make a lot of money out of i
t
 and while I was there - we were the first boys to have a ride in a Rolls Royce car, because a lot of people used to come down - well-to-do people you know, rich people - lord Langatta, Lord Harcourt Rose, all them people come down, of course it was more 
pity's sake than anything and - some big pot come down with this Rolls Royce and give four at a time a ride from the Chailey School down to Newark - Newark and Chailey station. And I can say that I was one of the first to have a ride in a Rolls Royce.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of living accommodation did you have there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Lovely. When we first went there we had a dormitory. The new boys had a dormitory Right, well - when you start - when we got there used a bigger hall - farmhouse it was - you - they say it was a t
ruant school at one time, but anyhow, they got this place, Kimmins, and - when you started you settled the first - the last one on the row down here, a table in the middle and a row down the other side, table, table, and a big table in the cent}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 e. Well - a
s you got on you worked your way down, 'til you go to the other end on the other side. When you got to the other end on the other side you went to the middle table and - what marvellous food you had there. We had an old sailor there, you know, on the sail
ing ships and he used to be our physical instructor. He used to learn us all the drill, you know, swo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
d drill - but not boxing. But when he went the other fellow who come he learned us boxing. Or taught us boxing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You did sword drills did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Oh I can still remember it. Yes. Oh yes. That was the old sailors in what - you know the sailing shops.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 This was cutlass drill not fencing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Cutlass. Oh no, we only had a stick. We'd have cut one another to pieces. No, it was only an ordinary
 copper stick like, guard, cut one, point, parry. You know, used to face one another, a line here and a line facing see. Yes. And of course when he left, he got so old - had another chap come, he come out here - some Lancers - I don't know what numbered L
ancers, anyhow, he learnt us being and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How many staff were there there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
They had a matron and a nurse. We had a chap done all the dirty work, a mental case he was - we had - instructor and his wife used to do the cooking and all that, h
e used to do all the drill and that. Mr Sykes and a - an assistant. That was two, four, six - about eight altogether.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 And how many boys would there be there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 I think there was about twenty of us there at that time. Now - there's about four hundred. I'm going there, I've got the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614  what}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
name, I'm going there. I go every year. Yes. I bought - they send me a lot of tickets you know, sweepstake tickets, seven and sixpence or half a quid's worth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How did you get on with the staff at that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
All right. Yes, we got on all right. I don't - only had one quarrel there. When I refused to wear his college cap. I refused to wear it because she said, look, you can't go around in the rain without a cap on. I'll get one of Anthony's - Anthony's '
ll do you. 'Cos Anthony - she had two sons, Anthony and Brian. Both went in the Navy and - Anthony was at college and so was Brian. And - I wouldn't wear this cap. Only had a cloak - a short pair of knickers, a c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 at you know, ordinary coat like and if trained we got a cloak.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Was this a uniform?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, that was the uniform. And - shoes. Thick - soles as thick as that, proper clogs they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How were you treated there on the whole do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Very nice. Yes, very nice. As long as we behaved ourselves it was all right, but if we misbehaved ourselves we copped it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of punishments did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Caning. Yes, caning.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of hours did you work at that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well we used to do lessons in the morning from nine 'til about ten, then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of lessons would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh, reading, writing or drawing or - ideas - if we got any ideas in our heads for - a bit of furniture or something like that, we used to put it on paper. And then after ten o'clock
, we used to go from ten o'clock 'til twelve on the bench. Planning and whatever job we were on, 'cos I say they started us on toys, simple things. The first question they asked you when you went there, I remember, it - Mr Sykes, he was the headmaster, we
ll Thomas, he says, you want to be a carpenter? Yes. He said, but you're not going to be a carpenter, you're going to be a cabinet maker. I said, I want to be a carpenter, I said, I wanted to be a boot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 maker I said, they sent me down here to be a carpenter,
 I said, now you want me to be a cabinet maker. All right, he says, all right, that's enough. So he says, have you ever done any woodwork? I said, yes sir. What did you do? I said - oh we made our own motors. Motors? I said, yes, four wheels on a box - on
 
four wheels you know. Oh, he says, I see. How did you bore the holes? I said, with red hot poker. Yes. He said, a good idea, he said, did you ever set the house alight? I said, no. No. What else did you used to make? I said, well I used to make hutches fo
r
 my white mice. Oh did you? How did you make the box? Told him how I made a box you know, got an old wooden box and took - turned it upside down, I - took the glass out the - out the picture to make the front. Good ideas he said. Now look, he said - if I 
- see that chisel? I said, yes. He said, look - and he hit the chisel the wood split, so he said, what did that do, did that cut it or split it? I said, split it sir. Good idea, he said, we're going to make something of you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your parents show any interest in your work at this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did they come and see you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
They come once while I was there. Only me mother, not me father, he wouldn't be bothered with it. He mother come down with about another twenty mothers. Oh what a lot they were. They nearly got half drunk before they come in, we heard singing and that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 This was a busload organised by someone was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes, the - Mrs Kimmins got it - invited all our mothers down to this party you see. We had a sort o
f party - we'd been singing for six months to learn these songs and when you come to the day I forgot 'em. Oh we had all the Glory Ada songs you know. Of those on our ships and that. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you ever used to go home for a holiday from there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. They always used to send us away. For a fortnight, a month, two months sometimes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Where did you used to go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well one place we went, Hastings, Hearts of Oak, convalescent home. And another place I went Pembury, Tonbridge. We was s
ent there - looked after by the biggest - well I don't know who she was - Miss - Mrs - Miss Penny, had a great big mansion, had about twenty servants there, I stopped - I remember - well they didn't live in the mansion, I lived with one of the of the vill
a
ge people in Pembury and - I can remember her saying, come round and have a look at this - looked in a - a - a gate, an iron gate and I remember saying, that's where all the boy's are what they burn. Well only about eighteen months ago we went on a coach 
r
ide from the mission where I go and - coming through the coach driver got a mike and he says, look, over there, he says, where they used to burn 'em at the stake, the women. I thought to myself, oh is that what that - you know, the village lady tried to -
 
I couldn't make out what she was chat - it was in the dark, I couldn't see nothing. Anyhow after I found out it's where they buried 'em - what was remains of 'em - what they burnt at the stake. All women. Pembury. Another place we went, Caterham. Went the
re for a month. Some well-to-do person in Caterham or Coston. Near Caterham Valley I know. She paid for me for the month. Another place - Caterham - Hastings - oh several places I went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So you didn't do too badly for holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, no, no. Very well. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - being such a harem-scar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 m I realize it now but - having the run of the streets like that in those days, there was always a clique of us, about twenty - none of their mothers and fathe
rs looked after 'em, like me, see. And we had the run of the streets, fetched ourself up in the best way we could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 you think you benefit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 ed from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 In a way, yes. Yes, in a way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 While you were still at school did you go to any theatres or music halls or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
No. Pictures. Yes. Penny gaff. We used to go to Victoria - you know where the - Vic is in - Waterloo Road? Used to go there every Monday night, penny mad house. South London, Canterbury, go to all the music halls, the Elephant and Castle.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 While you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You used to go in the music halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 This is what you used to earn your pocket money for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your parents ever give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - my father did, he was good hearted mind you, he was good hearted but - I suppose he got with his mates and he didn't care about us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after her house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. No. She was such a quarrelsome woman. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 The neighbours didn't help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 If your mother was ill or confined to bed, having a baby or something like this, how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh that I don't know because I was the last one. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh - sons and daughters always near one another. They all lived round Waterloo and Blackfriars, nearly all the lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How much did you see of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh we see quite a lot of them.
 They used to come round to see may - see the house or the mother or the father but - they used to all go out in the pub drinking. Of course all my brothers and sisters big drinkers. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your parents have friends?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well only drinking friends, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did they share the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your mother have friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well they always get a clique. 'Cos she - when she went to Convent Garden they were all together, shelling peas and that and they used to
 come drinking together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So your parents would go to the same pub and have the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes. The same crowd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were friends often invited into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, for the reason why we nearly always had one room - I can only remember once we had two rooms in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 Vern}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 on Street, London Road, the only time I can remember my mother having two rooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So you'd live most of your life out of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did friends ever call in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. 'Course they was never in - never long in one place you see, always got chucked out or turned out or something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your parents ever go visiting friends at their house or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Many people divide society into different social classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 In that time before 1918 did you think of some people as belonging to one class and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - even in the slums where - where we was brought up - we had our classes, because - some were - went to wor
k regular, didn't drink and - get away from my window, get away from my door, get down further. There were another class you know oh - you were a f'ing so and so and all that lark, see, different types you see. Although we lived down them slums.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So there were really two types in the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - near enough. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What would you call the other classes at that time as you remember them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What - the slum class or ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 The whole of society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 The whole of society? Well, t
he majority were a working class but they worked for a very low wage. The other classed didn't a want to go to work or couldn't go to work, they thought more about going th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 eving. See they were drove to it really, see, they - no jobs about and they've gone
 after jobs, no. Well they were drove to it, in my opinion. 'Cos I mean to say my father used to come home and say - well, I don't know no money. Go round - ask - Lily whether she's got any money. I went round to Lily - see that was a daughter - my father
 says to her, have you got any money you can let me have? So she said, what? Not me, she said, I - if I had a mint of money she said, I wouldn't let him have it to get in the pub. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How about above the working class, doctors and people like this, what would you call them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Doctors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Or any upper class people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well they didn't mix with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were you aware of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. 'Cos as I say, I lived in St Margaret}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 s Court and I used to earn many a penny because - the
 boy used to come in - come round to me and say, mother said she wants you. Say, what does she want? I don't know. All right, I'll go. She'd say, would you go over to Thomas's hospital or Guys hospital and tell them that I shall be needing - you'll be nee
d
ed in about - couple of hours, something like that. Well I used to dash over to Guys hospital - I knew where to go - go in - Mrs so and so says would you go over there in a couple of hours. What another one? She only had one last week. You know. That was 
- oh I had that job many many times. But - as for medicine - used to pay three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
pence - well nine out of ten used to write a note, father's out of work, we've got no rent and all that, well they used to get the bottle of medicine free in Guys - well, I suppose all the hospitals, but I know for a fact that Guys did do that. Yes.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What about the other people, were there any posh houses round about where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - not posh but they were - you know - they had a regular job, they were the lucky ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 But still working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Yes, yes, the working class but they were lucky to have a job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How about these people who interviewed you to go to the cripple school, what class of people did they belong to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What, who used to come round to see us - sort of social workers, that sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You say this truant officer chap took you and there was a load of men round a bit table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of class were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh they were a - well educated - well up in their -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What would you call them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well, I should class 'em as well educated, college people and - they knew what they were talking about, because that was their regular job, interviewing all these children to find out that the real trouble was. They found out my real trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, I can't say I can, it was nearly always the one class. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were you ever told to touch your cap or show respect to anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh yes. Yes. I remember that - we went to Brighton, you now, a day's holiday, and - this lady took me down on the promenade and as we come off the promenade onto the - up onto the pavement - I walked on the inside. So she
 says, Tommy - that's not right. I says - what's not right? She said, when you walk with a lady, she said, you always walk on the kerb side because if a - a - carriage and pair or a - cart comes along and - and the horse went down, splashed the mud on, yo
u're supposed to walk on that side to save the mud splashing on them. Oh several times I was told - told about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 In the area you lived in who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - the shopkeepers mostly. Because - you could - if 
you behaved yourself you could always get a bit on tick. Or - the majority of shops, you could go there for a soup ticket see. And - if you was one of the naughty boys, which I was - many a time I was refused, but I always knew I'd get one at one shop, th
e - a big linen drapers shop name of Brooke's in the Borough High Street. I always got one off of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did they used to give them away themselves or were these tickets paid for the by the borough and given out through the shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, not by the borough. By the - the shopkeeper theirself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 This linen shop would give out so many tickets a day would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 This linen drapers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How did they work it, did they give out so many tickets a day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Only one. One boy one ticket. See - this Brookes' was the biggest linen draper in the High Street Borough at that time. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 And they'd give so much to charity in this way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - yes, that's why they used to help the boys and girls and the slum people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of class would you put the shopkeepers in then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well I should class them as middle class people. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 And what would you call the educated ones, would they be middle class or something different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 The educated ones? Oh they were the upper class, and they let you know it as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How about clergymen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh yes, we had clergymen in galore round here. We had one in the Borough High Street we had a clergyman there - Reverend Martin. In - as I said in St Margaret}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 s Court we had a square and of a Saturday ni
ght - there was a - this square - had a barrel organ in the middle, there was the Reverend Martin borrowed a chair off of one of the neighbours - talking about God and that and - over the other side there was a couple of fellows stripped to the waist figh
t
ing, yes, I had all that, and us kids are there - this Reverend Martin, he was - well he was - different to anybody I knew, because they started building Coronation stands on St Martins Church where Little Dorritt was - you remember - heard - read Dickens
,
 Little Dorritt. Well you go in there you'll find their handwriting - because they started building Coronation stands on the graveyard - he tried to blow it up. But he was caught in time. Right opposite was a big shop, if anybody died in the family everyb
ody had new mourning. Men had new suits, the women had new dresses, all black. But you don't see 'em now. I mean to say, do with a black band now don't they.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Would even these poor working class buy black suits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes. And you know how they mo
stly got their money to buy? Off the money lenders, penny in the shilling. Oh it - plenty of money lenders round. They used to sit in the pubs - rows of rings, used to walk in - morning Mrs so and so, whatever her name was - nearly all women - would you l
et me have a pound. Pound enough? 'Cos they only got twenty shillings, one and eight}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
pence for that pound. If you had five pound well they got five times as much. They knew they'd get it back. Otherwise it - it's spoiled for good, the word went round, no other money lenders would lend them money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 These money lenders were mainly women were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Women - yes, nine out of ten were - were woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did they live local?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh they lived local - local, yes. Yes. They were - neighbours really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 They just managed to get hold of a few bob?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
And started, yes. I knew one person - one woman, she started ha'penny in the shilling, well she didn't last long 'cos she had all the other penny shilling after her. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of class would you call teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Teachers? I should class them as middle class. Mrs Ware - that was our teacher at the - the Old Kent Road cripple school, she was a middle class and she didn't have any sway with her, she used to let us - invite us down to her place and
 her husband was there. She had no children and - she'd give us a fine blow out. Of course we had to walk all the way to Tulse Hill, Brixton. So we want that tea, but we appreciated it. When I walked in there with a black eye, she sai}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 d, you've been at it again Tomm}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 y. Oh yes. Oh she - I class her as middle class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How about employers, where would you put these, people who owned a bit of a factory or something?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh they - they were the upper class. Yes. They were the upper class. As I say when they 
were upper class they let you know they were upper class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of people would you say went to the church in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - mostly were hypocrites. In regard to the Catholics - we was disgusted with their ways. Because I mean to say the
y used to come straight out of the church, across the road into the pub, run they did to get over to the pub quick and the first thing they done was - certain women they got hold of see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were there many Catholics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Only round the district where I
 was in the Borough, cos - Borough at that time was one mass of Irish, it was Irish colony almost but they shifted from there to Brixton and - the - coloured people took after them, there's no Irish really at Brixton now, they seem -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 In those days before 1918 was there any trouble between the Irish and the local people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes. They had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 Fein}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 . And - 1912 - '13, we had the - when Churchill divided it. 'Course they let Ireland have one half and the other half belonged to England. The I.R.A., have you heard of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Was there any religious trouble in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No. No. No. Mind you there were a lot of different religions. Chapel and churches of all different religions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Would you say there was any difference in the class of people who went to chapel and the class of people who went to - church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
In regards to - difference in the what? No. 'Cos the - there were a lot of - people tried to do - be good, such as the - the Gospel Lighthouse, we had a - a man there, well-to-do man, s
omething to do with insurance, Mr Bowen, he was the man that - sent all - most of them away to Canada, sent my brother away. And - well-to-do, we only had like an old paper warehouse where we used to go for our tea and that, and old warehouse, up - we had
 the upstair}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
 part where they sort paper - waste paper out, but - he found enough money to open a new one and it's still there but not as a mission hall. See. It's died out. It's let out as a warehouse now. And - sort of a - offices, yes. Oh yes, yes. They 
nearly all died out. In Stamford Street, near Sainsbury}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
s, there was one, two, three - four - five - six different religions, chapel, church, you know, not churches really, more chapels. They had the Irish lot down there and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember names of any of the chapels, the religions?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, I can't say I do, I never took much notice of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
You say there were these two classes within the working class, one rough and one respectable, do you think that one group felt superior to the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh yes. Yes. I mean to say, the - those who would go to work regular - they didn't used to look down upon the others - you know, I mean to say they wouldn't mix with them see, because I mean to say they wouldn't let their children play - with us. They
 used to send 'em to somewhere - give 'em a couple of coppers for a ride right the way out of it, keep them away from us roughs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 A difference?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You say t
he respectable working class looked down on the rough working class, can you remember any sort of similar thing between craftsmen and their labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - yes - those tradesmen, they were tradesmen mind you and - they used to say to a labourer, yo
u know, say on a building job, the carpenter would say - or the plumber or whatever he was or the painter, he - he'd say to a labourer, huh, once a labourer always a labourer. See, and that - the labourers didn't used to like that. They - they didn't used
 to like it. Yes. Oh I've heard that many a - many a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 They'd really rub it in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, they didn't class anybody any different. Classed everybody the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you think she would have been aware of the social structure or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well I don't suppose she troubled.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 At that time was it possible to move from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes, by dressing different. 'Cos we nearly all had a - chokers on, handkerch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 efs, but if you put a collar on, that made all the difference, because - I was sent to a job and - I had to go and see him 
to get the address where I had to go. So he says - well - Tommy, he said, you can't go like that. So I said, - oh Dulwich he wanted to send me, it's a long way and I lived in digs at that time. He said, you can't go like that. I said, why? He said, you mu
s
t put a collar on. The only time I ever put a collar on was when we went for a treat, ha'penny collar, and the - you know, irritated us, not used to it, used to tear 'em off. And when he said to me, well you'll have to have a collar on, I said, yes, all r
ight, I'll go home and get one. I never went back to - I never went back over this collar.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes, yes. These missions we go to, we always class them as ladies. The women. And the men as gentlemen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Was this because of their money, their wealth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
No, the way they used to speak to you mostly. Or they'd help you, you know, me being a cripple they'd say, oh - you sit over there Tommy and - you won't get hurt. I'd say
, oh I'm all right, I - I won't get hurt. Oh well you take that chair. You know, used to feel it in your heart you know, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 It was more the way they acted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Yes. But I think it was their true way, they wasn't putting it on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Just genuine good people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, I've always thought they were genuine. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you get many police round about the district you were in as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Police? Not half we didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How do you think the police treated people in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well
 - they treated us in a decent way but if we was obstreperous well they treated us in an obstreperous way. In regards, you know, we'd been playing banker you know with a packet of cards down the street. Copper used to come along and he used to stand there
 
and say, all right Tommy Jones, I know your name and I know where you live. And he'd start rolling down, we'd snatch our ha'pennies and pennies, whatever we were - bit or cardboard. Well you didn't used to trouble about the cards because they were only a 
h
a'penny a pack and away we used to go. But - he used to stop, pick the cards up, tear them up - and it was - all right Tommy - always Tommy Jones. We had a ; one down there, they called him hock of bacon, a big store - well - tidy size stores - grocery an
d
 this 'ere - nobody knew his name so we nicknamed him Hock of Bacon because - this woman went in this stores and she nicked a hock of bacon. Well - the shopkeeper, he held her and of course the police station, Stones Inn it was called then - sent a boy - 
one of the - the boy you know who worked for him, over to the station to get a - a constable there. And as it happened to be it was Hock of Bacon. 'Course that was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 not his name. Well Hock of bacon come down, he says - what's the trouble? So the shopkeeper s
aid, she stole a hock of bacon. Hock of Bacon said, ah, poor woman, she must be hungry. Shopkeeper said, I can't help that, he said, I'm missing so much stuff, he said, I must charge her. Oh let the woman off. He begged and prayed to let the woman off. Bu
t, no, the shopkeeper wouldn't have it. Well he had to charge her, so they named him Hock of Bacon, that was the only charge he had while he was in the police force. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So you think on the whole they were fair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh policemen - yes. I class 'em 
myself better than what they are today. I do. What I found - 'course today you'd read the case and that case - and - them days they didn't trouble about running you in and all - you know, the kids. Even the drunks they used to let off sometimes, give 'em 
copper to - go on home you go and get into bed, see. They don't do that today. They're in their glory if - when they get somebody inside. Difference in the two times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were the coppers more or less the same ones all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. They all had the
ir beat. They used to come out the station all in line and they used to be dispersed here and there at their beats you see, but that stopped years and years ago that stopped. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 But in those days you'd get used to your local copper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. We kn
ew where - exactly where the coppers was. Today you don't know who's who. And nine out of ten almost in civvies. Very few civvy - in civvy clothes those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You had a lot of different landlords at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh dear, oh lor'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What did you think about landlords in those days in general?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Was only one decent landlord and she was a lady. Well you know what I mean, she kept a little shop and - she let the rooms out - empty - empty rooms out over the shop and - used to go down there for a farthings}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3631160\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
worth of milk or - ha'oorth of bread or anything like that and - I went down, I always paid the rent, my mother always sent me down to pay the rent, I was honest there. Mother sent the rent book down. Well now and again my mother used to say, go 
down and tell her that - could she let the rent go 'til next week, pay two. Well I used to go down, she used to say, that's all right, yes, quite all right. See? And she was a decent one. But the majority of them used to mostly Jews. All these slum houses
. You go - if you didn't pay the Jew he'd have you out - he'd wait on your doorstep next - next pay day and if you hadn't got the two weeks rent - out. They'd put your furniture out in the street. Oh yes. But they're not allowed to do that today.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you pay the landlords or did they have collectors to do this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, all the slum landlords had to collect their own rent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 They used to come round themselves did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. 'Course nearly - everybody only had one room. If you
'd two rooms or - you thought you had a mansion. 'Course the rooms were only - three shillings or three and six a week. One room mind you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Do you remember as a child feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You were conscious of your poverty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Yes. Yes. I've seen my mother setting down brooding, where's she going to get this and where's she going to get that. And I used to say, mother, got a ha'penny? Get out of it, get out - I've got enough troubles now. I'v
e got the rent - I've got to find this, I've got to find that, she said, I've got nothing to pawn. Get out of it. Of course I flew out, I knew what temper she was in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What did you think about this as a child, can you remember how you felt at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - I used to get wild with her, you know, I used to call - under me breath I used to call her everything. Yes. But of course being kids you don't think do you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you get much help from the Guardians or the parish or a charity at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - my father went and chopped up wood many a time to get relief. He used to go down - well my mother used to go down mostly and - look - he ain't been home for three days - we've got nothing to eat. I've got - you know - how many children I've got tw
o or three children, what she ever had, they're hungry. Right. Used to get a - a loaf, butter or something like that - not much. When your husband comes home you'll tell him he's got to come straight down here. Well when he did come home my mother'd say, 
y
ou've got to go to the - Guardian, Relieving Officer. Well he used to go down. Right. He didn't used to come home. My mother used to go down to him, he ain't home - he ain't come back again. He said, no, he's in the casual ward. He's in for three days cho
pping up wood for the food you've ad. Yes. That was the system then. Oh they had 'em - every - well about - every hundred yards these casual wards, in the Borough way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did this happen to your family very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Well I can remember - only
 just remember - you've heard of - what was the name of that - you know where Oliver Twist supposed to ask for more? Well it's still there now. What was the name - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614 f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
 - famous - oh - anyhow, I can just remember my mother carrying me, 'cos I was only very 
small, carrying me and knocking at this pair of doors, big doors, the door was opened any my mother carried me in and that was the last I see of my mother, he got hold of me and they put me on a spring bed and away my mother went and where she went I don'
t know. That was in where Oliver Twist supposed to ask for more. It's still there now but - oh tumbling down. And on the other side of the street they had a - a woman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 s lodging house. Three hundred women lived in that lodging house. All the filth of the earth, drags of the earth. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How did the Guardians treat you in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Well - they used to give you a bit to carry you on. Told you not to come up too many times and all that. But that was - as I say, that was - people were drove to go thieving.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What was their attitude towards you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh very abrupt. Very abrupt. They bullied you. Bullied you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh sometimes when I see them bullying my mother I used - almost cry and - I used to creep out out of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 They'd come round the house would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes, they'd come round to the house. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What would they come round the house for then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 See what you had. If you had anything decent they'd tell you to pawn it or sell it. Yes. It ain't -
 I mean it ain't so long ago - 19 - in between the wars, if you had a piano, you went to see them the relieving officer, you was told to get rid of it. Not give it away but sell it. To make up money to keep yourself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 When there was someone in the dis
trict or in the court that people disapproved of very strongly was there any special way in which they showed it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Oh yes. They'd stick around for the purpose. You know, used to be about four or five women and one used to - bully one used to go a
nd knock at the door. "Why don't you clean your windows?" See. 'Course the woman'd say, "you mind your own business." 'This mine, you're showing the court up." Showing the court up! "What; do you mean showing the court up? You're the one that's showing th
e court up." And she - the bully one'd say, "'ere - hear what she said? Mother S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
ith, hear what she said? I'll punch her in the nose." Of course it come to a fight, and it's terrible to see women fighting. Awful. Oh remember many a fight down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 They'd do this to try and force the person to move would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. And nine times out of ten they done it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Sometimes people tell us there was a thing called rough music, people if they disapproved of the goings on in a house they'd go round 
with pans and make noises outside the windows?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh with parties you mean? Parties?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 No, just to get people to go, as a way of showing that they weren't liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. They used to get the kids to throw mud on the windows. They'd break 'em, w
e'd break windows. Very often we used to. 'Course they was more afraid than anything, here - of course they used to get out. Of course you could move every day in those days, today - well I'm here, this is my last home if I lived another twenty years in a
 manner of peaking, but in those days, my mother's lived one - moved once a - once a week or once a fortnight. Yes. - Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 If the neighbours didn't like someone they'd encourage the kids to do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes. Oh they'd make it so uncomfortable for 
them they were glad to get out of it. Because they could get away easy then you see. 'Cos all these estate - agent, they had their offices, all you had to do was to go in and say, have you any rooms? Yes, there's a list over there. See, well they had a li
st of empty rooms or a couple of rooms, but it was mostly one room. You was well off if you had two rooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You told me when you were at school you used to earn money by chopping firewood and selling envelops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Were there any more regular ways you had or earning some money, did you ever have a part time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 What sort of things did you used to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - other things - we used to get a barrow and we used to go down Bronte Place, Walworth, and we used to buy - well
 we used to get a barrow, 'course it's only about four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
pence or sixpence a day to get a barrow and you - you had the weight on the barrow - two or three hundred weight on that. Well we used to go down Bronte Place, Walworth, that's a small turning out of E
ast Lane Walworth, you know, big market place there, and we used to buy salt, hard}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
stone, vinegar - what's that stuff that - poison stuff - anyhow we used to buy this stuff, I forget the name, and - we used to go round - all round Ken}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 ington shouting out, salt, hearthstone, vinegar. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Hawking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes. Oh there was always two of us at doing that. Yes. Hawking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How old were you when you'd do this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - about - ten or eleven. Yes. Oh yes, well we had to you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you ever do anything like milk boy or a paper round or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
I used to run papers. I used to buy three copies for a penny and of course the papers used to come out with a horse and van then - a two wheeled cart like, and of course t
hey were very quick horses or ponies, very fast and - we used to wait at this spot where they used to pull up, three copies, penny. Well you used to dash round, sell the three, you earnt a ha'penny. Well you'd dash back again, when he come up again, you'd
 get - you might be able to have six copies, see, well that six copies you earnt another penny. All them tricks. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 So during your school age you were on the make for a few coppers all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 You said you left school early and you had this van boys job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Yes, I was about thirteen - just turned thirteen - yes, well about thirteen and a half.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 How did you get that job, do you remember?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Well - 'cos most of the boys, they used to work at the railways, van boys
. Well one of them said to me, 'ere - over the railway yard, he said, the yard shed - he said, C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
ofton - comp - Compton their name was, they used to London to Compton - Cobham, well they had a name like Cobham, was a van boy. Why don't you go after it? I'd say, no, I'm not fourteen yet. Don't matter, tell him }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 ou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
re fourteen. 'Course they didn't ask for birth certificate, we had no - insurance cards or anything like that then. I went over. I said - you want a van boy sir? How old are you? Fourteen sir. Oh. 
When can you start? Now sir. Four o'clock in the afternoon, now sir, you know, so eager to get the job. And - all right. Start in the morning. Right. Well we used to work Borough Market, Billingsgate Market and all round. 'Course - it was - hours and hour
s and hours - eighteen hours a day sometimes. All for five shillings a week. But my mother was fair, she used to give me half a crown out of five shilling. 'Course the other - other half crown went in beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 Did you think that was a fair wage at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Oh didn't stop to think. And yet I enjoyed it. It was quite exciting going round calling in shops, have you anything at Cobham? Yes, here you are. Sack of stone, weighed about two hundredweight. I said, I can't lift that. No, know you can't but yo
u're - your car}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11863073\charrsid13784614 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
man will. And he - he did lift it an all. And he got a trolley and got it up a little higher and he got it on his back. Like a sack of soda or a sack of flour. Bag of flour. Weighed two hundred and forty pounds you know. Yes. Cement - we ha
d cement, fish, bacon, eggs, everything all mixed up on our van.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13981439 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 It was like a carrier service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9258539 TJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14097773\charrsid13784614 
Yes, that's right. Like Carter Patterson started, when they first - 'cos he only started with a two wheel cart and - simply the same thing. But the only difference was he had a four wheeled van.
